{
  "doc_id": "27513",
  "text": "The PTEN tumour-suppressor gene, located on chromosome 10q23.3, encodes a lipid and protein phosphatase, which exerts its lipid phosphatase activity through dephosphorylation of phosphoinositide-3-kinase (PI3K) products, which in turn decreases the activity of kinases downstream of PI3K such as Akt and mTOR and its protein phosphatase activity on proteins of the mitogenactivated protein kinase pathway [CITATION_1] . Thus, a loss or reduction in PTEN activity leads to increased phosphorylation of key cellular proteins involved in cell-cycle progression, metabolism, migration, survival and spreading [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . PTEN also plays a role in maintaining chromosomal integrity [CITATION_4] .",
